There are lots of leaps of logic in this story that don't add up. The idea of a standup routine would be recorded and submitted to TV Network, and they'd think it was worth airing is a stretch. The idea that 3 people being killed on a subway would be a catalyst for a city-wide revolt is as crazy as people thinking this movie's release would lead to anarchy. And that's part of the point. We are not supposed to believe this narrative. This pity party but also self-aggrandizing tripe is the type of stuff that a psycho would come up with to justify his actions. I can see why this movie is loved by many and hated by many others. For me, I found it interesting at times, and overly pretentious in others. But hey, that's life.

watched Joker (2019) from director Todd Phillips and starring Joaquin Phoenix, Robert De Niro and Zazie Beetz. There's only one thing that I could say about this film and that is that it's a masterpiece, a 10 out of 10. Everything was spot on from the story, the acting and the music. The film is about Arthur Fleck and he has a laughing disabilitie. He wants to be seen but he feels like he's not. Arthur did some horrible things and eventually became the Joker. The story is dark just like some other DC films. It's a good thing that it's dark because how else would you tell the story of the Joker. The story really focusses on Joker and not on other heroes or villains in Gotham like Batman. Joaquin Phoenix was fantastic as Joker. He played Joker so good that he's in my top 3 of Joker performances of all time. His acting made him so good. The laugh that he did was incredible. The amount of weight he lost for this role is insane. You could see his bones so that is how skinny he was. His dances were also great. The stair scene when he's dancing on them is the best scene in the movie. The make-up artists did an amazing job with the clown make-up. The clown make-up and his costume is different from other Jokers. The sets and film locations are beautiful. The darkness and sometimes the bright colors looked great in every scene. The music is also great. 'That's Life' is perfect for Joker. I got goosebumps from every scene when 'That's Life' played because it felt epic. I would highly recommend this film for everyone who loves DC Comics and superhero movies. The story is great and the acting is fantastic. The Oscar was well deserved for Joaquin Phoenix and always remember: "That's Life."

Joker is a gritty, intense character study that dives deep into the psyche of Arthur Fleck. Joaquin Phoenix delivers a mesmerizing performance that‚Äôs both heartbreaking and disturbing. The cinematography, score, and direction all add to the film‚Äôs heavy, unsettling tone. While it‚Äôs not an easy watch and can be uncomfortable at times, it‚Äôs a bold, artistic take on a familiar villain that lingers in your mind. A must-see for fans of psychological drama.

Joker explores the central character's gradual descent into madness. Initially, he is depicted as awkward and downtrodden, struggling to find his place in a society that seems set on marginalizing him. As circumstances and personal afflictions beyond his control continue piling up, he becomes increasingly unhinged, ultimately giving way to the chaos and anarchy that defines his character. The film's realistic approach to the making of the most famous - or perhaps infamous - madman in comic book history is both unsettling and haunting.

This film simply showed a huge middle finger to all expensive blockbusters. Joker is a very dark, very heavy, very telling film that carefully swings between mass appeal and arthouse. This is an amazing take on the Joker's origin story. Some may say that it isn't really a Joker movie and is basically just a random bloke called Arthur Fleck masquerading as the Joker, but the way I see it, it is. The Joker's philosophy is that all it takes to become like him is one bad day. This movie basically embodies that philosophy. All it took Arthur to begin the path to becoming the Clown Prince of Crime was one bad day where he got fired from his job and beaten up by 3 people on the subway. It fits the character well. Even if Joker 2 takes the plot in a very different (and still good) direction, this movie still holds up as an amazing Joker origin story.

Joker - 10/10. Masterpiece. I don't like calling films masterpieces or incredible very often, but I also can't get this film out of my head since I watched it. Joker is one of those movies that sticks with you. For what it was trying to do (creating a serious drama driven comic book film), the film passes with flying colours. First and foremost, this is NOT a movie for everyone. It's rated R for a reason, and it's subject matter and the manner that the film progresses quite possibly be off putting for some people. It's a harrowing experience to see how Arthur Fleck lives from the beginning of the film, and it is also deeply disturbing how he transforms from a depressed outcast to becoming a horrible and maniacal villain. Joaquin Phoenix takes what Heath Ledger brought to the character in The Dark Knight, and creates a different look for the character. You progress from feeling bad for the guy to becoming genuinely terrified of what he will do/think next. Joaquin does an amazing job of creating the journey of Arthur with just subtle changes to his body language and delivery of dialogue from scene to scene. Todd Phillips does a spectacular job of reinventing his visual and story telling methods (even with the obvious nods to previous Martin Scorsese films). The cinematography is incredible and the music is haunting. It's a film that holds your attention and refuses to let go. Probably the best film of the year and one of the best of this decade! Joker 2 alternative theories: Was Harleen a honey trap? Did anyone consider the potential for deceit, when the bully guard (Played by Brendan Gleeson), in an uncharacteristic kind act, effectively takes Arthur to meet Harleen (Lee) at the choir? As the film progresses, we find out from Arthur's Lawyer who Harleen really is. Did she lure him in with him with a false personal story or do they really have a connection, a Folie a Deux? Arthur questions Harleen who further reels him. Arthur then ignores his lawyer's motherly warning. At this point he totally smitten with Harleen. In my opinion Arthur's lawyer was the only character who genuinely cared for him. She was wise to the institution harm at Arkham: she understood the neglect and torture that was inflicted on Arthur by the guards, and psychological torment belitting him, e.g., they mock how easy he was to catch, through his unstrategic crime to kill someone live on TV. Arthur's lawyers pleads insanity and builds a defense case highlighting his abusive childhood, to help him avoid the death sentence. It was Harleen that drove the wedge between them. Ultimately Arthur fires his lawyer and represents himself dressed as the joker. He talk about folie! Harleen being a honey trap would also explain how she manages to bend the rules of the prison regime over and over again. For example gaining private access to his cell where the films' sex takes place (its depiction is the antithesis of porn: bleak and over in a flash). The only problematic scene would be the fire during the movie night at Arkham. If Harleen was really working as some kind of undercover agent, then would it be plausible for her to go that far to destroy property? It was a reckless move but it paid off in gaining Arthur's trust. On reflection it was another example of her managing to evade consequence to her actions and instead is released from the jail. Ultimately Lee breaks up with him, at the very moment that their fantasy to live together as a family could have become true. She appears to be disappointed in him, for taking an unprecedented move to admit in the court room that he's not mentally ill. But I think that was exactly what she wanted to happen. I think she was a honey trap, planted whether working alone or undercover in cahoots with New York state and her doctor father, on a mission to lead him to Arthur to his demise. I think sabotage Arthur's chances of winning his freedom during the trial: the State of New York versus Arthur Fleck.

Although Joaquin Phoenix did a fantastic job of portraying the writer and directors vision of the Joker, I believe the idea of the Joker has been too Humanized. Heath Ledgers Portrayal of the Joker brought us up to the level that could be considered human, just the right balance, in the world of super humans. Fast forward to Jared Leto's Joker in suicide squad and hes a gangster with gold chains and tattoos, Overly humanized. This movie obviously tries to introduce the Joker as just a regular guy, twisted by his upbringing and the lack of respect from the outside world. Yet, it fails to depict the Joker as the brilliant evil genius that he is. In comics and other movie sources it is made clear that the entity known as the Joker has never been diagnosed with any mental illness because of how he can manipulate the therapists trying to label him. In front of one therapists he will portray himself as a cool and calculated sociopath, to another a manic depressive with suicidal tendencies, to another a hysterical, maniacal person completely lacking control of his emotions or a cold blooded Psycopath. It was this skill of manipulation after all, that turned Harlene Quinzel into Harley Quin, the Jokers protege. So, great acting throughout the movie, unfortunately failing due to the script missing the essence of The Joker.

Arthur is the ultimate joker, an unreliable narrator with a fractured mind, his story told through inventive camera angles and Edward Hopper lighting. His mind dances unravelled through an atmospheric score and underlining lyrics of popular songs, as events that might have happened unfold before us, horrific, darkly humorous, clues to his background scattered like the detritus of a ransacked room. Phoenix gives us as much nuance as we can stand, colouring in right up to the corners, his physicality informing us as much as his words, earning every accolade he received for this. Joker does not conform to the standard fare of comic-inspired film, concentrating on a tiny corner of a dirty laundry basket rather than any kind of wide redemptive or narrative arc. It is not joyful or predictable, but it does leave a lasting impression of a truly troubled mind told in an intriguing way and is a significant contribution to the comic-book oeuvre

Watching this again five years later, which ironically, this film had just turned five years old yesterday (today being October 5th), and I will say what I'd thought this was indeed a masterpiece, I kinda had some second thoughts since I'm a little wiser as I'm getting older. Not to say that this is a terrible movie, but rather still one of the best movies out there when it was released in 2019. We can already say that the acting was amazing, the cinematography was amazing, even the setting was amazing. Not to mention how this sets in about mental illness and social problems when it came to delivering the message from Arthur himself. Funny, if you remember a cartoon called Duckman, I couldn't help but imagine the character of the same name say the same lines as Joker made while also keeping that line in mind since we live in a dysfunctional internet culture of today. Sure, you could say society is as mucky as it normally does, whether you're sane or not. I am aware about Joaquin Pheonix's strict diet to play the role, but one thing I have to say is that it is a job, after all. Sometimes you're dedicated to do as request or turn it down and walk away as it's always been such for decades, whether you work with Hollywood or anywhere else, big or small. Now, about some things that does cross my mind is having to think about the actions that Arthur has done off camera does have me guessing, but technically you'd have to use your sense of imagination to figure out if certain events had happened or not like when he was at his ex-girlfriend's apartment room. Also, I was curious on the jump cut at the ending, which I won't spoil too much, but curious how Arthur had gotten to that after a certain time of event as the ending rolls on. But I digress. For the most, I still had a fun time, had some good laughs and does keep me laser focused from start to finish after seeing this again for the second time, especially before I see this sequel for myself. I'd give it nine dancing Arthur's out of ten. 9/10.

This is a very difficult movie to review. Which is both a good thing, and a bad thing. I went in with an idea that this was going to be a strange movie, and I was not disappointed. The positives were pretty much the same as the previous Joaquin Phoenix interpretation. A stellar performance, although getting a second Oscar for playing the character would probably be a reach. The story was well written, and although I wasn't a big fan of the first movies ending, it seems that this one a slightly better one, despite the fact that it came from out of the same left field corner alley. I was also skeptical of the fact that it's a musical in the truest sense of the word. Although I admit I was pleasantly surprised that chose to use mostly classic show tune numbers. I'm not a huge Lady Gaga fan, but I thought her and Phoenix played well off each other, resulting in a "decent" vocalization performance on both parts, which gave the movie a realism that you don't usually see in musicals. I would have liked to have seen Lady Gaga portray a more "traditional" rendition of Harley Quinn, but it's hard to say if she would have been able to pull it off, and still keep a realistic tone in the movie. The fact this, like the previous movie, was only loosely based on the DC comics, was not an issue, although anyone watching this with said notion will be disappointed as they probably were if they saw the first. I'm not sure if this is a primary interpretation of either of the films, but they seem to imply that certain people, for better or for worse, have the ability to "polarize" communities as a whole to the point that they lose control of those that are captivated by the mere existence of their fixation. *Joker* is a brilliant character study with Joaquin Phoenix delivering an outstanding, raw performance. The film's strength lies in its exploration of Arthur Fleck's descent into madness, blending gritty drama with Gotham City's eerie atmosphere. I love how it keeps you guessing what‚Äôs real and what‚Äôs imagined, making the audience question Arthur's reality. However, it's a strange choice to connect it to the DC universe, as it feels disconnected from Batman or the traditional Joker character. Story-wise, it heavily mirrors *Taxi Driver* and *The King of Comedy*, which makes it feel less original, but the execution still works. Despite being a bit overrated, it remains an engaging watch with strong visuals and intense emotional depth. It may not be groundbreaking, but *Joker* offers an easy-to-follow, gripping character study that holds up on multiple viewings. Phoenix‚Äôs performance alone makes it worth watching again and again. 3.5 stars.

As a psychotherapist and a person with mental illness, I can say subjectively, that anyone who's suffered mental health issues will understand the depth of this movie. It's slowly paced, but it is a brilliant take on severe mental illness and how society treats those who are mentally ill as "outcasts". To those who have an empathetic nature, has gone through mental illness (and is aware of their illness, aka not in denial), Joker will resonate with you as it depicts a character who you may see in yourself.

I can understand why this can be polarizing. I can see why someone would see this potentially as glorifiying Mass shooter types, or painting mental illness as old fashioned Norman Bates crazy stereotypes. But it's much deeper than that an is a deconstructive character study done 70's style on what could drive someone insane who is responsible. Is it nature or nuture? Are we born mad or made mad or a bit of both? Even after the great plot twist it's never clear what is real and what isn't. It's a portrait of madness and the fallout asking uncomfortable questions. It's one of the darkest if not the most disturbing comic book movie ever made. But also an All Time Classic. Really the only issue is it fits ALOT of ideas into under 2 hours extremely well but it can feel a stuffed more than bloated but the editing is really good still. It's cinematography is inspired by the likes of Se7en and Fight Club and does it admirably. The supporting cast is very good but almost comedically over the top "Evil" and mean. But Phoenix steals the show and gives an amazing performance. It is fasinating watching him go down the rabbit hole of madness and the deeper it goes the more riveting it becomes. Everyone should give this a try once. It will 100% leave an impression even if you don't love it.

The genius of a mentally unstable character in a world that could happen tomorrowü§° The strength of Joker's (2019) film is still, above all, Joaquin Phoenix as the Joker. The character is emotionally charged and disturbingly authentic. Phoenix's body language, voice and facial expressions take us deep into the mysterious and painful world of Arthur Fleck. Phoenix so immersed himself in the character that this is reflected in interviews years after the film was made. Let's hope that only in his mind is the character still in action. When it comes to why it's simply brilliant the answer lies in the fact that most of the film is based on a worldview through the eyes of a maniac. He does evil and is evil but doesn't realise it himself. But aren't there people like that around us in everyday life? In a sense, the Joker is right. Who is competent enough to say what a comedy is. If we ourselves laugh at something inappropriate on a daily basis then we too can feel the mockery of others. However, why do these people have the right to say what and how things should be. In the film directed by Todd Phillips, the story was also very thought provoking. When you look at the madness that a member of a downward spiralling society, who no one cares about, has to deal with, you start to think to yourself, what are my behaviours when I see a 'different' person. You never know what problems a stranger has to deal with both mentally and physically. The Joker is also a visually striking film. Gotham City is portrayed in a dark and decadent tone that has a chilling effect. The film's cinematography, set design and costumes create a tense atmosphere that fully engages the viewer. However, this is the film's biggest problem. It is too focused on one character and the acting of the supporting cast leaves a lot to be desired. Personally, I am a big Robert De Niro fan, but this was definitely not one of his strongest roles.

Joker is a fantastic film, and a compelling origin for Joker. The whole film was enjoyable, though I would say that the second half is far better than the first half, and it's not particularly close. If the whole movie was as good as the second half, it would probably be a five-star. That's not to say the first half wasn't compelling or good, but it just couldn't really match the second half. Joaquin Phoenix's acting is nothing short of amazing, with his near-perfect portrayal of Arthur's descent into madness, which is a great time to watch. The overarching plot is also very well written, witch kept my eyes glued to the screen for nearly the entire runtime. This film was also really lacking in side characters, with almost all of them being very forgettable and uninteresting, which really left only one good character (albeit one very good character) carrying its entire 122 minute runtime. Besides these flaws though, Joker is a fantastic origin story for one of the greatest villains in media, and a great film. I can't wait to see what's coming next in the sequel.

This is the most unpleasant movie experience I've had since the first IT movie a couple years ago. My hopes were high considering the awards attention it got - culminating in a Best Actor Oscar for Phoenix. But this is an empty, superficial movie that doesn't offer any context about violence beyond what the average viewer would bring to it. I can't begin to understand the adulation this received. I won't fault Phoenix's work here - he is as committed as ever. But this is yet another case of a brilliant actor being rewarded for the wrong film. This is an ugly movie, both aesthetically and beneath the surface. Comparisons to TAXI DRIVER were made upon its release; and while I think TAXI DRIVER is a bit overrated, it is miles ahead of this movie, and I didn't find any similarities beyond a disgruntled protagonist. If you want to see a movie about the destruction of a man due to the world around him, please check out Jake Gyllenhaal in NIGHTCRAWLER instead. De Niro appears very uncomfortable in a supporting role that obviously will be compared to Jerry Lewis in THE KING OF COMEDY. This is bleak, unremitting and ultimately predictable. A crushing disappointment!
